            <h2>Measurement and Analysis</h2>
            <p>
                Measuring biochemical oxygen demand requires taking two measurements:
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li>Initial dissolved oxygen measurement (taken immediately)</li>
                <li>Final dissolved oxygen measurement (after 5 days of lab incubation)</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                The difference between these measurements represents the amount of oxygen consumed by microorganisms to break down the organic matter present in the sample during the incubation period.
            </p>
            
            <h2>Common Sources of BOD</h2>
            <p>Sources of biochemical oxygen demand include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Topsoil, leaves and woody debris</li>
                <li>Animal manure</li>
                <li>Effluents from pulp/paper mills, wastewater plants, feedlots, and food-processing plants</li>
                <li>Failing septic systems</li>
                <li>Urban stormwater runoff</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h2>Troubleshooting BOD Measurements</h2>
            <p>
                When encountering problems with BOD values, consider these factors:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><span class="highlight">Calibration:</span> Calibrate instruments once daily before readings. Ensure no water droplets on probe tip and use a clean, water-saturated environment.</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Probe Care:</span> For polarographic sensors, maintain fresh electrolyte and membranes. For optical sensors, periodically check the paint layer on the sensor cap.</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Warm-Up Time:</span> Polarographic probes require 5-15 minutes warm-up before use.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h2>Special Considerations</h2>
            <p>
                Different strategies are employed for specific sample types:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Varying dilutions and diluent seeding</li>
                <li>Using nitrification inhibitors to distinguish between carbonaceous and nitrogenous demand</li>
                <li>Special handling for toxic and chlorinated samples</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                When properly used, the BOD test provides reliable wastewater characterization. While newer methods offer quicker estimates, the standard 5-day test remains the regulatory benchmark.
            </p>
